t the emission arises from the\ninner disk ($<$ 50 AU) and lower surface layers of the disk where the gas and\ndust are coupled. The [OI] 63 \\mu m is fainter in transitional stars than in\nnormal Class II disks. Simple SED models indicate that the dust responsible for\nthe continuum emission is colder in these disks, leading to weaker line\nemission. [CII] 158 \\mu m emission is only detected in strong outflow sources.\nThe observed line ratios of [OI] 63 \\mu m to [OI] 145 \\mu m are in the regime\nwhere we are insensitive to the gas-to-dust ratio, neither can we discriminate\nbetween shock or PDR emission. We detect no Class III object in [OI] 63 \\mu m\nand only three in continuum, at least one of which is a candidate debris disk.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Aug 2013 00:28:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-17"}
